        <article class="blog-post">
            <h2>On ADHD and Creativity</h2>
            <p><strong>Date:</strong> 17 Dec 2024</p>
            <p>ADHD often feels like an ever-shifting kaleidoscope of interests. Today I might be researching coral restoration, tomorrow diving into Middle Eastern geopolitics. Turning this cognitive jumpiness into a strength can be tough, but what if this eclecticism fuels something truly original? The key lies in structure—just enough planning to harness the spark, not extinguish it.</p>
        </article>
        
        <article class="blog-post">
            <h2>Time Travel & Counterfactuals</h2>
            <p><strong>Date:</strong> 10 Dec 2024</p>
            <p>Thinking about “What if Hitler never rose to power?” or speculating on a ‘crystal ball’ technology to forecast human decisions might sound like idle daydreaming. But such exercises stretch the imagination, helping us understand how history is shaped by contingency and human agency. It’s a reminder that the world’s tapestry is woven from countless “what ifs.”</p>
        </article>
        
        <article class="blog-post">
            <h2>Early-2000s Internet Nostalgia</h2>
            <p><strong>Date:</strong> 05 Dec 2024</p>
            <p>There’s something comforting about those old layouts, the garish GIFs, and silly Geocities pages. It was a time when personal expression trumped polished interfaces. I’m trying to recapture a bit of that spirit here—proving that personal authenticity can shine brighter than any sleek modern template.</p>
        </article>
